Here, $f(x, y) = \left( e^{x - y} + 1, -e^{x - y} \right)$.

$\begin{align}
P_y &= -e^{x - y} \\ \\
Q_x &= -e^{x - y}
\end{align}$

Because $P_y = Q_x$, the vector field $f$ is conservative.

Here, $f(x, y) = (e^{\cos(y)}, e^{\cos(x)})$.

$\begin{align}
P_y &= -\sin(y) e^{\cos(y)} \\ \\
Q_x &= -\sin(x) e^{\cos(x)}
\end{align}$

Because $P_y \neq Q_x$, the vector field $f$ is not conservative.
